In a paper published in February 2017, an educational policy researcher recommended that educational reforms should pay attention to the crucial question of the language of instruction and implementation of language policy in education.
Mother tongue holds a strong footing in the society since it is used for informal communication and neighbourhood conversations. While the opinion is always divided among parents, teachers, scholars and other stakeholders in the education sector on the use of mother tongue for instruction, a research published in 2013 showed that when used as a mode of instruction in school, it improved the quality of education; eliminated unnecessary dropouts.





The current socio-linguistic situation seems to have given English an undue hegemonic advantage over other languages. Mostly in sciences, it has dominated the instruction in lieu of an alternative system in which students could be actively engaged and learn using their native tongue. Couldn’t this lead to defaming and degrading mother tongues in the longer term? 
Academic achievement
Usually, those who oppose the idea of “ethnolinguistic diversity” in colleges cite huge costs associated with changing language of instruction, the large investments needed for intellectualisation of the language, and production of instructional and supplemental materials in mother tongue.



