To them, it would cause confusion; that lack of direct translations of core scientific and mathematic terms may result in a language barrier, preventing students from excelling. One interlocutor confided in me that it may even exacerbate socio-ethnic stigmatisation.
However, methinks that the omission of mother tongue, especially in colleges, could adversely fuel marginalisation of monolingual mother tongue speaking prospective students and even teachers who do not have a solid grasp of English.
The totalitarian use of English as a means for students to acquire literacy is a practice that could lead to an ineffective educational system in the longer term or unnecessarily hamper academic achievement. 
As research has shown, students acquire literacy most efficiently in their native language. The more highly developed the first language skills, the better the results could be in the second language, because language and cognition in the second build on the first.
Some studies have even looked at it from the angle of economics. Maintaining English as the sole language of instruction in sciences has been shown to be a handicap on the economy since it results in low educational participation. There’s a correlation between weak economic development and low educational participation.



